<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-800-332  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 800 332.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  August 1990 v23 n8 p103(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Image processing on the Macintosh. (Software Review) (IPLab,Ultimage, Image) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Morris, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Three image processing packages for the Apple Computer Macintoshare IPLab, Ultimate, and Image.andP;  IPLab, $499 from SignalAnalytics, is the most suitable for a general course in imageprocessing.andP;  IPLab supports frequency domain manipulation betterthan the other two packages.andP;  This package is highly recommendedfor anyone who wants to do sophisticated image processing or whois building an image processing course laboratory.andP;  Ultimage,$2,990 from GTFS, has more emphasis on quantitative analysis andis more likely to be the choice of people, such as medicalresearchers, who do not have the time nor expertise to implementanalysis programs in an extension language.andP;  An advantage ofUltimage is that all Ultimage windows can be printed, a feature ofconsiderable interest in scientific applications.andP;  Image, in thepublic domain or $100 from NTIS, requires a high level ofsophistication to customize and simplify complex repetitive steps.andO;Image provides standard image manipulation features, but does notdo fast Fourier transforms.andP;  All three programs need a MacintoshII with 8-bit color cards and a minimum of 2 megabytes of memory.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (computer programs)IPLab (Computer graphics software)Ultimage (Scientific software)Image (Computer graphics software).andO;Topic:     EvaluationSoftware PackagesImage Processing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>